A year later Erhard von Queiss, nominated (Tschackert, No. 134, ii. 35), but never confirmed, Bishop of Pomesania‚ 1523-†29, put out his [No. 92] Programme of Reforms, 1 Jan. 1525 (Tschackert, ii. 101, No. 300). The prelates were aided by the preachers, who arrived in Konigsberg 1523—4 (ibim, Nos. 141, 237), Jo. Briessmann 1488— †1550, and Paul Speratus, 1484-†1551. Prussia thus acquired its new religion and its new political status together, as was observed in [No. 93] a letter of Andrew Bishop of Premysl, 1524—7, to the Nuncio in Hungary (Acta Yomz'cz'ana, vii. 249). On 30 May 1525 the Bishop of Samland (Tschackert, ii. 120, No. 356), ancl 23 Oct. 1527 the Bishop of Pomesania (ibid. ii. 194, No. 565) each gave up his temporal lordship. They retained their spiritual jurisdiction-—administered now, as before, by officials —till, 1550, Superintendents were substituted for Bishops because they were cheaper (ibid. i. 113; iii. 263, No. 2374).
